1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:19,840
John has talked about how you should associate hashing with integrity.

2
00:00:19,840 --> 00:00:40,660
John has talked about how you should associate hashing with integrity. So let's play

3
00:00:40,660 --> 00:00:45,820
that out. Let's use a scenario here where I want to send an email to my future

4
00:00:45,820 --> 00:00:50,760
business partner here at Nigel. So I want to send Nigel an email with a contract in place

5
00:00:50,760 --> 00:00:55,400
because he and I are going to start a business together, horse trading. So I want to send an

6
00:00:55,400 --> 00:01:00,320
email containing a legal contract and I want to make sure that Nigel receives exactly

7
00:01:00,320 --> 00:01:04,400
the same contract as what I have sent because it's a business contract. I want to make

8
00:01:04,400 --> 00:01:10,640
sure that the message has integrity. So I create my message here, my email. I write

9
00:01:10,640 --> 00:01:17,880
the email and then I hash the email and I attach that hash value to the email. So now

10
00:01:17,880 --> 00:01:24,400
this email here contains the message of the email and a hash value at the bottom. And

11
00:01:24,400 --> 00:01:31,160
now I send the message over to Nigel here. He receives the message. Now he wants to make

12
00:01:31,160 --> 00:01:35,880
sure that the message, the message that he received has integrity. So how is he going

13
00:01:35,880 --> 00:01:42,280
to do that? Well, he will hash the message that he received and he will compare that

14
00:01:42,280 --> 00:01:47,480
to the hash value that he's just calculated to the one that I attached to the email. And

15
00:01:47,480 --> 00:01:53,440
if those hash values match, then he'll know the message has integrity. So this looks

16
00:01:53,440 --> 00:01:59,320
good, right? We've used hashing to prove the integrity of a message. But there's actually

17
00:01:59,320 --> 00:02:05,360
a big problem here. And to explain this problem, we need to introduce another actor into our

18
00:02:05,360 --> 00:02:10,400
little scenario here. Here's the additional character that we need in our little scenario

19
00:02:10,400 --> 00:02:15,760
here, my malicious munchkin. Here's what's going to happen. We're going to replay the scenario

20
00:02:15,760 --> 00:02:21,920
over again. I'm going to create an email containing some information that I want to have integrity.

21
00:02:21,920 --> 00:02:26,560
That I want Nigel here to know has integrity. So I'm going to write the message. I'm going

22
00:02:26,560 --> 00:02:31,880
to attach the hash value to the message. And I'm going to send that message to Nigel.

23
00:02:32,280 --> 00:02:36,680
My malicious munchkin here is going to perform a malicious munchkin in the middle attack,

24
00:02:36,680 --> 00:02:41,640
a man in the middle attack. She's going to catch the ball. She's going to intercept the message.

25
00:02:42,680 --> 00:02:48,920
Now, she's going to modify the message because does integrity provide, if we've just hashed

26
00:02:48,920 --> 00:02:55,800
the message, does that provide confidentiality? No, she can read the message. And what she can do

27
00:02:55,880 --> 00:03:02,200
is she can modify the message. And then she can just remove my hash value, calculate a new hash

28
00:03:02,200 --> 00:03:09,000
value and send it to Nigel. So that's exactly what she's going to do. She's going to modify the message.

29
00:03:09,000 --> 00:03:14,520
And then she's going to forward it onto Nigel. Nigel is going to receive the message.

30
00:03:15,400 --> 00:03:20,040
He's going to hash the message that he received. He's going to compare that to the hash value that's

31
00:03:20,040 --> 00:03:25,480
attached to the message. And what is he going to find? He's going to find that they match. And so

32
00:03:25,480 --> 00:03:31,480
Nigel is going to assume that the message has integrity. And this is the really big flaw here.

33
00:03:31,480 --> 00:03:38,040
This is why you cannot use simply a hash value attached to a message to prove integrity.

34
00:03:38,040 --> 00:03:42,760
Because any little malicious munchkin here could have intercepted the message in transit.

35
00:03:44,040 --> 00:03:49,560
Change the message, take it off my hash value and replace it with her own or their own and

36
00:03:49,640 --> 00:03:54,120
forward on the message. And the receiver has no idea this has happened.

37
00:03:55,480 --> 00:04:01,400
So this is why we do not simply use a hash value to prove that a message has integrity.

38
00:04:01,400 --> 00:04:07,560
Instead we use digital signatures. So this is what the section is about. We're going to talk about

39
00:04:07,560 --> 00:04:13,800
what we can use digital signatures for and how we create them. So let's start with what can we

40
00:04:13,800 --> 00:04:22,360
use digital signatures for? They provide three services, integrity, authenticity, and non-repediation.

41
00:04:23,960 --> 00:04:28,520
So using digital signatures we can achieve integrity, authenticity, and non-repediation.

42
00:04:28,520 --> 00:04:33,640
Let's start by describing how we create a digital signature. It's actually remarkably easy.

43
00:04:33,640 --> 00:04:39,960
There's only two steps involved. Step one in creating a digital signature is the sender

44
00:04:39,960 --> 00:04:47,080
hashes the message. When you hash a message it produces a fixed length message digest.

45
00:04:49,400 --> 00:04:54,360
So that's step one, hash the message. Step two, and listen very carefully here.

46
00:04:55,160 --> 00:05:01,480
Step two, the sender encrypts the hash value with the sender's private key.

47
00:05:02,760 --> 00:05:06,840
And that produces a digital signature. That's all a digital signature is.

48
00:05:06,840 --> 00:05:12,840
It's simply the hash value of the message, the file, encrypted with the sender's private key.

49
00:05:13,480 --> 00:05:18,600
So how large are digital signatures? They're actually quite small. Because what are we encrypting here?

50
00:05:18,600 --> 00:05:23,640
We're just encrypting a hash value. And how large your hash value is? Well, we've talked about

51
00:05:23,640 --> 00:05:30,280
differing hashing algorithms like MD5 and SHA1 and SHA256. They're creating message digest hash

52
00:05:30,280 --> 00:05:39,000
values between 128 bits, 256 bits, maybe 512 bits at the maximum. So all that we're encrypting

53
00:05:39,000 --> 00:05:45,640
here is a few hundred bits of data, a really small amount of data. And the encryption process does

54
00:05:45,640 --> 00:05:52,360
not add much the size. So digital signatures are very, very small. So let's go through a quick

55
00:05:52,360 --> 00:05:57,880
diagram that shows how this actually works when you have a sender and a receiver and they're

56
00:05:57,880 --> 00:06:04,040
using a digital signature to send a message. So here we're going to use an Alice and Bob diagram.

57
00:06:04,600 --> 00:06:10,120
And we're going to start with the message. So here is the message that Alice wants to send to Bob.

58
00:06:11,480 --> 00:06:18,840
Alice wants to have this message to have integrity, authenticity, and non-repediation. To achieve

59
00:06:18,840 --> 00:06:24,600
those three services, Alice is going to create her own digital signature. There are two steps

60
00:06:24,600 --> 00:06:31,960
required to create a digital signature. I'll step one, Alice will hash the message, producing a

61
00:06:31,960 --> 00:06:38,920
fixed-length message digest. Step two, the sender Alice will encrypt the message digest with her

62
00:06:39,560 --> 00:06:47,080
private key, producing a digital signature. So that's the only steps that are required to create

63
00:06:47,080 --> 00:06:53,480
a digital signature. Alice can now attach that digital signature to the message and send it over to

64
00:06:53,480 --> 00:06:59,320
Bob. Now I want to ask you something and I want you to pay very close attention here.

65
00:07:00,280 --> 00:07:07,480
In sending this message with a digital signature attached, did we achieve confidentiality? Can anyone

66
00:07:07,480 --> 00:07:16,680
read this message? Yes, be very, very clear on this. Digital signatures do not provide confidentiality.

67
00:07:16,680 --> 00:07:23,880
Anyone can read the message. All the digital signatures provide are integrity, authenticity,

68
00:07:23,880 --> 00:07:30,840
and non-repediation. So to achieve integrity, authenticity, and non-repediation, Bob has to do

69
00:07:30,840 --> 00:07:36,600
some work with the digital signature. The first thing he has to do is decrypt it because a digital

70
00:07:36,600 --> 00:07:44,200
signature is ciphertext. So Bob is going to decrypt the digital signature with Alice's public key.

71
00:07:44,600 --> 00:07:50,520
And when Bob decrypts the digital signature with Alice's public key, he's going to get back the

72
00:07:50,520 --> 00:07:57,400
hash value that Alice created. And if that digital signature decrypted with Alice's public key,

73
00:07:57,400 --> 00:08:03,080
who's the only person in the world that could have created that digital signature, Alice with her

74
00:08:03,640 --> 00:08:09,480
private key. So if that digital signature decrypts with Alice's public key, what that proves is

75
00:08:10,040 --> 00:08:18,200
authenticity. Bob knows the message came from Alice. Now the next thing Bob needs to do is he wants to

76
00:08:18,200 --> 00:08:23,560
actually see if there's integrity. So what he has to do is he has to hash the message that

77
00:08:23,560 --> 00:08:29,000
he received. And he needs to compare the hash value that he's just calculated to the hash value

78
00:08:29,000 --> 00:08:35,000
that he received in the message from Alice. And if those hash values match, Bob will know that

79
00:08:35,000 --> 00:08:41,560
the message had integrity. And when you have integrity and authenticity, then you have non-repidiation

80
00:08:41,560 --> 00:08:48,520
of origin. Alice cannot deny that she sent the message because Bob knows it came from Alice,

81
00:08:48,520 --> 00:08:54,280
and he knows the message has integrity. So he knows the message came from Alice, and he knows

82
00:08:54,280 --> 00:09:00,120
the message has not been changed. Therefore, Alice cannot deny non-repidiation of origin that she

83
00:09:00,200 --> 00:09:07,720
sent the message. So that's how we use digital signatures. Okay, now that we understand digital

84
00:09:07,720 --> 00:09:14,120
signatures, let's replay the scenario over again. But instead of attaching just a hash value to the

85
00:09:14,120 --> 00:09:21,000
message, instead I'm going to attach a digital signature. So I'm going to write the message,

86
00:09:21,000 --> 00:09:25,480
and then I'm going to create a digital signature, only two steps involved. I'm going to hash the

87
00:09:26,200 --> 00:09:30,840
message, producing a message digest, and then I'm going to encrypt that message digest with my

88
00:09:31,560 --> 00:09:37,480
private key. And I'm going to attach that digital signature to the message. And then what I'm

89
00:09:37,480 --> 00:09:43,720
going to do is I'm going to forward that message and send that message over to Nigel. Now my

90
00:09:43,720 --> 00:09:48,680
malicious munchkin here being the malicious individual that she is is going to continue to be malicious.

91
00:09:48,680 --> 00:09:53,960
She's going to intercept the message. So she's going to intercept the message.

92
00:09:54,760 --> 00:10:02,040
And now, can she read the message? Yes, digital signatures do not provide confidentiality.

93
00:10:03,000 --> 00:10:08,040
So she can read the message. She can even modify the message, but here's the really important

94
00:10:08,040 --> 00:10:14,600
question. Can she change my digital signature? So she wanted to modify the message and then

95
00:10:15,560 --> 00:10:23,560
modify the hash value inside of my digital signature. Can she do that? No. Because in order to be

96
00:10:23,560 --> 00:10:31,400
able to modify a digital signature, she would need my private key. And I never share my private key

97
00:10:31,400 --> 00:10:37,480
with anyone under any circumstances. And so even though my malicious munchkin here can intercept

98
00:10:37,480 --> 00:10:43,480
the message, and she can read the message, and she can modify the message, she cannot modify

99
00:10:43,560 --> 00:10:50,200
my digital signature. So she could modify the message and forward it on to Nigel, but Nigel would

100
00:10:50,200 --> 00:10:55,240
know because he's not able to modify my digital signature. So when he gets the message, he would

101
00:10:55,880 --> 00:11:00,920
hash the message, he would decrypt my digital signature, and he would compare the hash value

102
00:11:00,920 --> 00:11:06,200
in my digital signature to the hash value that he just calculated, and they will be different.

103
00:11:06,200 --> 00:11:10,360
They won't match. And therefore, he will know the message has been modified.

104
00:11:11,160 --> 00:11:15,560
So by using digital signatures for preventing my little malicious munchkin here, our attacker

105
00:11:16,200 --> 00:11:21,640
from modifying the hash value. Now, there's one other scenario you might be thinking about here,

106
00:11:21,640 --> 00:11:28,360
and that is what if my malicious little munchkin here rather than trying to change my digital signature?

107
00:11:28,360 --> 00:11:33,400
What if she just stripped off my digital signature and attached her own digital signature?

108
00:11:33,400 --> 00:11:38,920
So she could modify the message, she could calculate a new hash value, she could then encrypt that

109
00:11:38,920 --> 00:11:44,040
hash value with her private key, creating her own digital signature, and the hash value in her

110
00:11:44,040 --> 00:11:49,320
digital signature is going to match the message. So she could do all of that, and then she could

111
00:11:49,320 --> 00:11:55,240
forward it on to Nigel. But here's the problem with that. As soon as Nigel receives the message,

112
00:11:55,240 --> 00:12:00,360
he's going to try and decrypt the digital signature attached to it with my public key.

113
00:12:01,640 --> 00:12:06,360
And if it's a digital signature that's been created by my little malicious munchkin with her

114
00:12:06,360 --> 00:12:13,000
private key, it is not going to decrypt with my public key. So Nigel, the receiver is going to know

115
00:12:13,480 --> 00:12:17,800
that this is not my digital signature, he's going to know that this message didn't come from me,

116
00:12:17,800 --> 00:12:23,000
he's going to know it doesn't have authenticity. So this is how digital signatures solve the problem

117
00:12:23,000 --> 00:12:28,440
of a man in the middle, a malicious munchkin in the middle, intercepting a message and modifying

118
00:12:28,440 --> 00:12:34,040
the message and just replacing the hash value. And so remember, digital signatures provide integrity,

119
00:12:34,040 --> 00:12:39,960
authenticity, and non-repediation. The final piece that we need to cover here is what can we use

120
00:12:39,960 --> 00:12:43,400
digital signatures for beyond just what we've already talked about with sending a message?

121
00:12:44,120 --> 00:12:48,280
Well, it can actually be used for all sorts of different things. They can be used for code signing,

122
00:12:48,280 --> 00:12:52,360
like we talked about earlier, so that you can know who some code came from, and that that code

123
00:12:52,360 --> 00:12:58,840
hadn't been modified and trans it. You can even use them for signing documents. There's

124
00:12:59,080 --> 00:13:05,400
many countries jurisdictions in the world that actually have laws on the books that allow you to

125
00:13:05,400 --> 00:13:11,720
use digital signatures to sign legal documents. And in fact, a digital signature is a lot more

126
00:13:11,720 --> 00:13:17,880
trustworthy than an actual signature, because a digital like an actual signature is not impossible to

127
00:13:17,880 --> 00:13:25,240
forge, but to forge a digital signature. What would you need? He would need the sender's private key.

128
00:13:25,240 --> 00:13:28,600
And as long as they've done a very good job of protecting that private key,

129
00:13:28,600 --> 00:13:41,160
it's basically impossible to forge a digital signature. So that's digital signatures.

